TY  - JOUR
T1  - Complexifying Organizational Theory: Illustrations using Time Research
AU  - Ofori-Dankwa, Joseph
AU  - Julian, Scott D.
Y1  - 2001/07/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2001.4845809
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2001.4845809
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 415
EP  - 430
VL  - 26
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We seek to enrich organizational inquiry by introducing an additional level of abstraction based on theory complexity. We develop four levels of theory complexity and anchor each with well-established theoretical frameworks and research streams. After identifying the contingency approach as the simplest, we progress through cycles and competing values approaches and arrive at the chaos perspective as the most complex. We use research on time orientations, polychronicity, and entrainment to illustrate the utility of such a ladder of theoretical complexity in provoking alternative research lenses and inquiry.
AB  - We seek to enrich organizational inquiry by introducing an additional level of abstraction based on theory complexity. We develop four levels of theory complexity and anchor each with well-established theoretical frameworks and research streams. After identifying the contingency approach as the simplest, we progress through cycles and competing values approaches and arrive at the chaos perspective as the most complex. We use research on time orientations, polychronicity, and entrainment to illustrate the utility of such a ladder of theoretical complexity in provoking alternative research lenses and inquiry.
